{
  "texts": [
    "Input driving circuits (Block 4)The colour of each pixel in the image (represented as n 2 × 1 column) is codified as a voltage that is applied to a row in the crossbar (i.e., wordline), as depicted in Fig. 4c, resulting in a vector V of analogue voltages V i.",
    "If the image is black-white (i.e., 2 possible values), the values of the voltage V i of each pixel will be 0 and V READ (V READ being a reference voltage defined by the application); however, the colour of each pixel can also range within a greyscale, which leads to a range of analogue voltages.",
    "For instance, the colour of each pixel in the 8-bits p×p images of the MNIST dataset (and hence, the colour of each pixel in the resized n×n image to be input to the crossbar) varies within a greyscale of 2 8 = 256 possible values (codified in binary representation from 00000000 to 11111111), meaning that the voltages to be applied to each input of the crossbar may take values such as 0V, V READ /256, 2•V READ /256, etcetera until V READ.",
    "Hence, an 8-bit digital-to-analogue converter (DACs) is necessary for each input to convert the 8-bits-code into a single voltage.",
    "When the ANN is employed to recognize other types of images codified with a different format (e.g., 24-bit), DACs of different resolution are needed."
  ]
}